<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>short in something • short of something</xh5><p> <i>short in something</i>—(also: short on something ) not having enough of smth.: Though I was at that time rich in fame—for my book ran like wildfire—yet I was very <u>short in</u> money. </p><p><i>short of something—</i>1. <i>= short in something: </i>Elizabeth, always <u>short of</u> money, railed against the required outlay. 2. not fully amounting to smth.: If the court does not deem it appropriate to inflict punishment, it shall adopt other measures <u>short of</u> punishment. 3. except for smth.: He will do anything <u>short of</u> murder to achieve his ends.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>short for something</b>—<i>used of the short version of a name:</i> “B-girls?” I repeated, “What are they?” “That’s just <u>short for</u> bar girls.”</p> </entry>
